-- Japan, Taiwan, Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-26T22:46:52Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-26/japan-taiwan-malaysia-thailand-singapore-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Financial markets in South Korea, China and Taiwan are
closed today for public holidays.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  Bank of Japan Governor  Masaaki Shirakawa  will speak at a
business meeting at 2:30 p.m. in Osaka, Japan. Shirakawa will
have a press briefing from around 4:45 p.m.  Hiromasa Yonekura, head of Japan’s Keidanren business lobby,
will hold a media briefing at 3:30 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
its report on the nation’s trade balance for August.  The Bank of Japan will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on the corporate services price index for August.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.995 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 84.33 per dollar at 7:43 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea: The government plans to sell 700 billion won
($606 million) of 20-year bonds today.  The yield on the 3.75 percent note due June 2013 was 3.44
percent. The won was at 1,155.25 per dollar.  Taiwan: The government is scheduled to report leading index
data for August today. The index declined by 0.2 percent in July.  The yield on the 1.125 percent bond due September 2020 was
1.21 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$31.62.  Singapore: The government is scheduled to sell S$3.7
billion ($2.8 billion) of 91-day treasury bills today.  The yield on the 3.25 percent debt due September 2020 was
2.02 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3258.  Thailand: The government will sell a total of 12 billion
baht ($391 million) of 28-, 91- and 182-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note maturing March 2021 was
3.24 percent. The baht was at 30.71.  Malaysia: The central bank will today sell 2.5 billion
ringgit ($808 million) of 168-day notes and 1 billion ringgit of
91-day Shariah-compliant debt. The government will auction 3
billion ringgit of Islamic bonds maturing in 2013 on Sept. 29.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.28 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0930.  To contact the reporter on this story:
